{{Other people|John Davies}}

'''John Clay Davies II''' (May 1, 1920 - June 17, 2002) was a [[United States Representative]] from [[United States Congressional Delegations from New York|New York]].

==Biography==
Born in [[Albany, New York|Albany]], he was the grandson of [[John C. Davies (lawyer)|John Clay Davies]], who served as [[New York Attorney General]].  The younger Davies graduated from [[Camden, New York|Camden]] High School, and attended the [[University of Alabama]] at [[Tuscaloosa, Alabama|Tuscaloosa]] and [[Hamilton College (New York)|Hamilton College]] (in [[Clinton, Oneida County, New York|Clinton, New York]]). 

He was editor of the ''Camden Chronicle'' in 1940 and 1941, and maintained public relations offices in Albany from 1941 to 1943. He was with the [[public relations]] department of [[Westinghouse Electric (1886)|Westinghouse]] Electric Corp. in [[New York City]] from 1943 to 1946, and was vice president of the [[Earle Ferris]] Co. Inc., in New York City from 1946 to 1948. From 1948 to 1953 he was a partner in a public relations business in [[Utica, New York]].

Davies was elected as a [[USDemocrat|Democrat]] to the [[81st United States Congress|81st Congress]].  He won a close election by just 138 votes, and served one term, January 3, 1949 to January 3, 1951. He was an unsuccessful candidate for reelection to the [[82nd United States Congress|82nd Congress]] in 1950.

After leaving Congress Davies served as Deputy County Clerk for [[Oneida County, New York|Oneida County]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Sworn in for County Post: Former Congressman
Becomes Deputy Clerk |work=Rome (N.Y.) Daily Sentinel |page=2 |date=January 21, 1958 |url=http://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%2023/Rome%20NY%20Daily%20Sentinel/Rome%20NY%20Daily%20Sentinel%201958/Rome%20NY%20Daily%20Sentinel%201958%20-%200288.pdf}}</ref>

He was later a writer and a public relations executive in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], where he died on June 17, 2002.

